24:47.826 --> 24:49.568
have recovered marvelously. I've been very 
fortunate. And so in the last several years, we're

24:53.714 --> 24:59.142
in effect involved in and interaction between 
oceans and seas. What sort of work have you done

25:02.341 --> 25:07.126
there that you think of particular significance?

25:09.468 --> 25:10.709
What's been the most important thing? What have 
you looked for? Well, I've found evidence of

25:11.670 --> 25:16.495
organized convection, evidence of roll 
vortices. Two papers have been published with

25:16.795 --> 25:25.263
clear evidence of

25:16.795 --> 25:25.263
roll vortices. This evidence is in the surface 
wind field. It shows an alternating of directions

25:28.147 --> 25:32.393
as these vortices move past a buoy. Then, for the 
first time, I've reported on the

25:33.374 --> 25:46.853
near-surface change in meteorological 
parameters and oceanographic parameters, which

25:33.374 --> 25:46.853
are associated with open and closed mesoscale 
convection cells. One interesting thing that's

25:49.217 --> 25:56.567
not of great importance, but I found evidence of a 
turd-ironal tide in winds, which hadn't been

25:49.217 --> 25:56.567
reported before. I've

25:58.133 --> 26:09.710
shown that over relatively short distances, wind 
statistics over the ocean can vary considerably,

25:58.133 --> 26:09.710
and that was not known. The usual thing is to take a 
weather ship and extrapolate a thousand miles all

26:09.750 --> 26:14.397
around it. You just can't do this.

26:19.126 --> 26:32.123
meteorological driving forces are subject to 
major changes in time and space that need to be

26:19.126 --> 26:32.123
studied if you're going to study any part of the 
RCNR action process.

