27:02.950 --> 27:07.756
you think weather prediction will come out of 
this? I think that, aside from resources in the

27:10.079 --> 27:22.354
sea, that the best opportunity for benefiting 
mankind that oceanographers and meteorologists

27:10.079 --> 27:22.354
have is in weather forecasting. And in order to do 
this, we have to understand air-sea interaction

27:22.374 --> 27:28.843
processes much, much better than we do at the 
present time. And this is one of the reasons we're

27:28.883 --> 27:32.367
working. How far away are you from long-range 
weather forecasting?

27:39.081 --> 27:41.985
Well, there are two ways of looking at that. One of 
the most pressing things is to improve our

27:42.045 --> 27:52.358
forecasting, say, from a four-day forecast to a 
five- or six- or seven-day forecast.

27:53.800 --> 27:54.861
We've been on A lot of people have been working on 
this, and no one seems to have come through with any

27:55.702 --> 28:00.089
breakthroughs. We're just sort of stuck on a 
roughly four-day forecast. But as far as

28:04.476 --> 28:18.317
long-period trends are concerned, six months in 
advance or a year in advance, I think the work of

28:04.476 --> 28:18.317
Nimaeus and a number of other people indicates 
clearly that we're going to be able to forecast

28:04.476 --> 28:18.317
trends a little better than we could before. But 
the most important, well, that's important in

28:19.968 --> 28:22.531
itself. But improving our weather forecasting by 
two days would make a tremendous economical

28:22.551 --> 28:30.140
impact on the country. Routing of fuels, 
electrical network management, all of these

28:31.582 --> 28:40.172
things depend on how weather changes around the 
country. And if we could do it in six or eight days,

28:40.493 --> 28:42.955
it would just be wonderful. But I'm not sure we can. 
And that's what we're all working on. And that's

28:46.440 --> 28:49.283
where your work is pressing presently. I think so.

